Obese kid's menu: doesn't eat sausages and dinners
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, with 9 percent of schoolchildren overweight and 5 percent of obese children.
Obese children usually come from families with unhealthy lifestyles, as the current survey showed.
Once again, it shows how important it is for the healthy development of the human environment in which he grows up and the patterns that he is surrounded by.
In obese children, for example, sausages appear up to half as often as in families with normal weight.
Fried fries had for dinner the day before the research related to an education event called Obesity is not a coincidence of more than 19 percent obese.
It is also not customary for fat families to play sports, but this applies to most of the families of today's schoolchildren - only 15 percent of the children replied that their parents will find time for active movement at least once a week.
A survey of 900 children
The survey took place at the end of last year's school year and was attended by almost 900 children from primary schools from all over the Czech Republic.
It was the second year of Obesity is not a coincidence supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 schoolchildren from the 4th to 8th classes have been involved in the project.
The proper diet and exercise in the family is one of the determining factors that causes a dramatically increasing number of overweight or even obesity children.
"Only half of the respondents, for example, said that they eat five times a day in the breakfast-dinner-dinner-dinner mode, which is one of the basic prerequisites of proper nutrition," one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast and no sausage at night
Experts point out that there are important and relative details for healthy development, such as regular family breakfast time.
At the same time, only 23 percent of schoolchildren’ families eat breakfast in the Czech Republic.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst part was finding out that a tenth of the households don't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is the basis of the right daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet sodas every day (70 percent).
Although more than 40 percent of the children interviewed regularly play sports, the result was less than half - 15 percent for their parents.
Build your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own menus from the offered options according to their own tastes and their own opinion.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy nutrition."
There are a lot of floury, meaty and sweet dishes among their favorite dishes.
"It is particularly alarming that sweet lemonade is popular," says the final report on the survey.
For lunch as a main dish, pasta was just over the poultry.
However, the children practically did not want legumes at all and the popularity of fish and lunch vegetables is low.
Adhesive to Health
At the same time, the survey showed that children are willing to adjust their eating habits if they get the right information.
"There was a significant shift in preferences towards the principles of healthy nutrition in many cases in the control group of survey participants who filled out the questionnaire after the end of the Obesity education lecture," the project said.
For example, sweet lemonade, where more children would have preferred ordinary water.
Children have also checked poultry and fish as the main meal of the day more frequently in the questionnaire and would limit sweet meals and dumplings.
