In Need for Speed: The Run is racing across America.
Review
Originally a carefree ride turns into a routine morning shift because of a series of completely unnecessary sloppy mistakes.
Ambition was largely successful, but it is of no use when no one seemed to want to do anything extra.
The new episode with the subtitle The Run had raised high expectations before the release.
He promised that the old race series Need for Speed would once again move a bit in a new direction and from playable demonstrations he appeared as a game that might not be in the genre of action racing just to number.
We were also wondering how the inserted passages would end up, in which the main hero would get out of the car and run on his own.
However, as is the custom of the NFS series, many are a little different in outcome than we expected.
They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole pulls down a few unnecessary mistakes that have been appearing in the series for more or less years.
So they're not actually mistakes, but rather an expression of some kind of incomprehensible laziness of developers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced into a story whose main hero Jack has certain personal issues and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You get behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco, and your job is to be the first to arrive in New York.
The idea brings with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then more than fifty races.
It follows that each race is on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don't get the feeling that the game is always the same.
Some of the environments are also very pretty to look at, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's not a world-class thing.
But driving across the desert, autumn landscape or high in the snowy mountains seems visually very pleasant.
Moreover, from time to time races are enhanced by some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you get caught in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you must be careful not to be buried by avalanches.
In addition, individual races are quite well set in succession.
There's only a few types, but that's enough.
For a while you are trying to overtake the desired number of opponents (actually classic race), then you are catching up again (classical fight with stopwatches) and then there is a duel waiting for you with only one opponent.
From time to time, the police will also get involved in this, which makes your efforts even more difficult.
The news is the passages outside the car.
It's more of an interactive animation where Jack usually runs away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right moments.
Nothing complicated.
But it will surprise you that these passages are in play much less than you would expect (in particular maybe only three).
In the end, it is for the benefit of the thing, because this element has no chance of becoming annoying, and in the context of the above mentioned, it ranks among the elements that augment the game.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of the previous parts.
This means that it is definitely no longer a big deal nowadays, but it cannot be said to be a negative.
If you're looking for a realistic simulation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
But the driving model is still quite well suited for the more active racing, although we could find better for the competition.
So far, everything is in perfect order.
But the problems are beginning to appear after a while.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer in order.
We do not expect this type of game to calculate complex deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how your car will behave, then everything is probably not all right.
Typically, when you drive over or pass cars in normal traffic, you can easily lick each other, but sometimes in an almost identical situation, your car ends up in wild pirouettes.
Or even flat out.
Thanks to the reboot system, it doesn't matter, but it will upset you reliably.
Restarts are designed so that if you smash or drive far off track, the game will throw you back to the last clue point on the track.
But there are only five reboots available in each race.
When you exhaust them, you have to start the race again from the beginning.
So it's more of a tool in case something goes wrong than you can rely on it.
Sometimes even restarts don't help, they'll solve it until the need to learn a given section of the race by heart.
The big flaw in the game is that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be driven in a specific way, otherwise you simply can't fit into them.
Other times, you will meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at the same place, whether you arrive first, fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
It pisses off especially in situations where you can see the opponent passing between two opposite cars in front of you, while when you get there, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
It doesn't matter when you get there, because it's "counted" so that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
Competitors have another advantage.
In all the time playing you will find several places where you, again regardless of the time, always overtake the same opponent in the same place.
It hits the most at the end of the game on the long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
The opponent must get there in front of you at any cost, apparently.
When you drive in front of you, you get a worse view of the cars, so at first, you're probably going to get a lot of smashing.
You can understand the intention to make the game more exciting and more adrenalineier, but the design is so obvious that it will make you reliably quickly disgusted.
And it's a shame, because even with a simple driving model, playing is fun and sometimes so actionable that sometimes you can't literally keep track of what's going on.
And it doesn't really matter whether the concept of 50 unique tracks, the race sequence, is responsible, so that boredom doesn't stand a chance, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to switch cars during races.
You have to watch out for gas stations near the roads, because that's where you can change the car, although in most cases you can get by with what you just have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars on straight motorways and exotic supersports for technical riding, for example on winding mountain roads.
With the main story mode goes hand in hand and mode of challenges, which are races in individual locations, which you know from the story.
Here you get not only medals, but also experience points into your profile, which is common for both challenges and story.
Various items are unlocked for the higher level of the driver: starting with cars and ending with backgrounds for the profile.
It is also linked to the online Autolog function, which compares, among other things, your achievements with other players and provides other community functions.
One other difficult to understand is the situation of the last race in the story.
With your car you can get to the subway tunnel (but be it), where you drive it in the dark on the tracks (but be it).
On the tachometer, the numbers are flashing between 150 and 200 km/h (let's be) and in that direction, a train of subways comes crashing in the back and scrapes you uncompromisingly.
At the editor's office, we can probably spend a few more days discussing whether we really didn't think a little bit about the game, or whether the authors think we're really that big of an idiot.
The technical aspect of the game is nothing special, but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases very pleasant and in some cases even great.
It is so saddened that in some of the tenser moments the images are falling, in some cases rather tragically.
However, this concerns mainly accidents with more participants, where continuous imaging would be no longer of any use to you.
The sound page is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to please the widest possible range of younger audiences, a soundtrack from the "every dog different village" category was created, but it is possible to assume that someone will not just buy the game because of listening to music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is so greatly embarrassed.
If the game were to avoid completely unnecessary mistakes, then we would not be afraid to say that The Run is the best work of the NFS in the last few years.
But this is how the game looks unfinished.
I'm sure it's fun, but get ready for mistakes to rub you in the eye with the power of airport spotlights.
