Brand story:
The IBM Innovator begins the second century of its existence
If someone were looking for a word that would best express IBM's strategy, the closest would be "longevity".
For the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution, it is a company perceived as very contemporary, and yet it has been established for a hundred years.
The foundation of this longevity was laid by the first head of the company, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already struck a password that many of the world’s problems can be easily solved if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became a print around which the life of the future giant (and also the name of the internal magazine, which began to be published in IBM in 1935).
It was also the foundation of Watson's carefully built corporate culture.
"For us from IBM, long-term thinking means continuous movement towards the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because she remained faithful to her basic values and was not afraid to change everything else around her.
This allowed us to transform technology, business, and society during our first centuries.
We hope that we can achieve even more in the second hundred," said Samuel J. Palmisano, the current director for the anniversary.
Worked-up system
Watson treated his employees in the 1930s, like the entrepreneur Bata in the Czech Republic - people from IBM were one of the first American employees to have paid leave, insurance from the employer, plus an elegant employee uniform and a sophisticated system to pay for the best inventors and traders.
The IBM has a long-term relationship with the customer.
The company was brilliant at extracting talent from the beginning - as one of the world's first companies, it abolished any discrimination, so she could choose.
