How prices of tours have developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
At that time, travel agencies in the vast majority only sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc, since travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus traveled on vacation to the sea in the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Society in Crimea near the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was possible to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel independently even within socialist countries.
If the citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise the individual way was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at the time, but it was necessary to stand in line overnight with a sleeping bag or to have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Still, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people" who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for the trip to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
By far, however, the Czechs most often spent their vacation in the Czech Republic, resulting in a large number of cottages and cottages that the Czechs acquired and this habit survives to this day.
Czech travel has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 the holiday in GDR or Bulgaria was our maximum, last year Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
The huge paradox that we no longer realize today is that it was not possible for us to travel freely to the most popular Croatia until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
Right from the beginning of the 1990s, visa requirements for neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, which triggered a huge wave of short-term visits mainly to Austria’s Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not get enough of trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for a while.
In Paris, for example, Czech trips slept in tent parks, as our incomes at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guest house.
A typical feature of Czech travel in this time was the carriage of own food, cans, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally purchase the Western currency after many tens of years.
However, our standard of living and the average salaries increased, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to increased travel demand, travel agencies have started to prepare charter tours regularly since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper because of the opportunity to negotiate quantity discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, Czechs already had visa-free contact with virtually all developed countries of the world, except the USA, which made our travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred in 2000, when thanks to considerable demand was sent from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exotics, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters fly with Czech tourists to warm faraway countries, this winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists, and thus our country has finally become one of the world's most advanced countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time (50.3%) and spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person on one foreign holiday for the first time in history, including the cost of their stay.
