Massacre on a personal level
An emotionally strong new book by Peter Englund called Beauty and Grief: The Confidential History of World War I (The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War) begins with such a long list of performers that you get dizzy.
One piece of advice on how to behave at that moment: Carefully rip this page out and make it a bookmark.
You will get to know all the people in Mr. Englund's novel story, and this list will serve you as a navigation - a kind of beacon - at times when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author describes it himself, quite fittingly, as an "antihistorical work".
It contains several very well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, but almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists, and debates on tactics and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, the author explains, like, "the book about what it was like." It mainly deals with "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods".
"Beauty and sorrow" combines the war experiences of 20 more or less dozen men and women, both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and officials.
Some of these people become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go crazy or die.
Their lives are shimmering like the flames of candles lit in a church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fate while others are extinguishing.
Mr. Englund's book differs from classic historical novels.
It corrects the notion that World War I was just about the fearsome trench fighting on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" is also a skilled exploration of other places where war dramas took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
Soldiers in this book solve problems with bees' nests falling on them, spending Christmas in the shadow of pyramids or struggling with the presence of tsetse flies.
Almost from the beginning, this is a very moving reading.
War consumes people's lives like some kind of natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina smelling of gunpowder.
When a gunfire starts to ring in the distance, and you're the woman who's home with her kids, run away or stay?
Who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is happening, not even why the whole war was unleashed.
"Vakuum resulting from lack of facts," Englund noticed, "was filled with conjectures, conjectures, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and sorrow" follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from CVs, letters and other already published materials.
The descriptions of their lives may sound both frightening and captivating, but thanks to the integration of tiny moments and details, they are absolutely alive and believable.
Many of them discuss hardship and dealing with it.
In the story of a German student, the author says, "Alternatives, all substitutes."
"A substitute for coffee, imitation aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It goes even further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
It refers to "mass made of pressed rice cooked in sheep fat (and supplemented with a false bone of wood), tobacco of dried roots and dried potato skins, wooden soles".
It mentions that there were "837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and bravery.
One American finds internal impulses for savagery and brutality in himself, and then declares about the war: "In the end, you will understand that this is human nature. Not sitting in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, evening newspapers or good books and pretending that this mask of yours represents civilization and that there is no barbarian hiding behind the starched self inside."
On the contrary, the British soldier realizes that he will most likely die soon and no one will even notice, let alone grieve.
"When you finally accept the sacrifice, you would at least expect it to happen in front of a grateful audience," he writes.
