Although Breivik could have acted alone, he was certainly not lonely in cyberspace: during the preparation of the attack he spent a lot of time at the computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists supporting right-wing groups on social networking sites.
After this summer's tragedy, scientists want to learn more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - you just have to go on Facebook.
"We realized that finding them isn't really that hard," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British research team on European digital populism.
The stock of personal information on Facebook is so extensive, says Bartlett that it was enough for scientists to simply use the advertising on the site, and thanks to that, they have determined with absolute precision the demographic group - something that marketing workers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team across Europe found half a million fans of right-wing groups, then they focused their attention on them and sent them advertisements, but instead of inviting them to the newly formed group or offering them some dietary products, they invited them to fill out a questionnaire that asked questions about their level of education, their relationship to violence and optimism in view of their own future.
Through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues managed to get results from more than 10,000 fans of 14 different right-wing groups in 11 European countries - without ever having to leave the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing research," Bartlett notes.
Some of the results are not so surprising: online followers of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are irritated by the increasing rate of immigration.
But on the other hand, "those who combine their online activism with their offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain constantly hidden behind the computer screen."
The work of the DEMOS team is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research teams, health scientists and political researchers use this site to study everything, from health problems to social trends that hide state updates, wall contributions and pressed "I like" buttons.
Facebook reports more than 800 million active users. Each of them provides three different data on average daily, which literally makes this social network "information supernova", which is behind the development of many new researches. The number of academic works in whose name the word Facebook is known has risen to almost 800% over five years ago.
For some scientists, it is the magic of Facebook that gives them the opportunity to study people without having to harass them on the street.
"It used to be that when you wanted to do a survey among the British National Party people, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to get to the side where they'd never let you go," says Bartlett.
"All this Facebook is breaking down - you're just going straight to them."
Others claim that the site can offer a way to identify and avoid a social-health problem.
In a recent study by Dr. Megan Moren of Wisconsin University, the research team found that university students who were discussing their drunken performance on Facebook were much more at risk of the problem of alcoholism than students who were silent about the subject.
Moreno suggests that peers of students monitor the site and come up with an offer to help a student who publishes too many drunken statuses.
"The problem cannot be solved if you cannot diagnose it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Dr. Moreno and director of the Center for Health, Behavior and Development of Children at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We have found a way to identify endangered children that we would otherwise not have a chance to discover."
Facebook itself constantly probes the data of its users.
The information team of the site has developed statistics on the relationship status and Valentine's Day, the election participation in 2010 and the National Satisfaction Factor (mainly using the information to which they had access - Internet freedom advocates have long claimed that the site should make its information treasure available for research and others).
But Facebook users know that the site follows them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you need to provide your personal information to the site.
But what if Facebook users become part of a research they don't even know about?
Scientists have clearly defined rules on how to collect data off-line. However, online data is accessible to everyone.
"I don't think most of the users ever thought that scientists could look at their profiles," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London Knowledge Lab, on a 2006 study he conducted using the public Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they were concerned, they took it as information between them and their friends."
Subsequently, it is also necessary to consider the question of methodology.
Even with off-line research, there is no guarantee that the subject is completely honest.
There is no way to verify on Facebook how much information on the profile and posts on the wall are true.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things," Selwyn explains.
That is why Selwin, who spent years researching new technologies, thinks that pencil and notebook remain the best possible tool to use in research.
"If you go out into the real world and talk to real people, it's something you can't replace," he says.
