But do not conclude that it is somehow difficult to spot and expose liars.
A trained lie identifier can reveal the truth from a sentence structure, small facial expressions, the way questions are created and their timing.
I have spent several years gathering scientific knowledge from a large and emerging sector on the recognition of lies, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that can be easily learned and can be of great help to you in today's difficult world - especially if your work responsibilities include hiring, holding interviews, negotiating or leading people.
Good liars can read well in others, let them slacken in vigilance, direct their emotions, and intuitively realize how the other side accepts them.
From research, we know that extroverts lie more often than introverts, that men tell more "self-centered" lies, while women tell more lies "focused on others" - mostly to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than single people (but the lies they say are usually "unspeakable").
We also know that if you are perceived as a sinner, others feel less guilty when they lie to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
