Thanks to him, he'll have later findings to compare them to.
Notice the posture of the subject, his laughter, his voice work.
You should know if someone routinely taps his feet all the time, so that you don't wrongfully accuse him of lying just because he starts to tap his feet in the middle of a meeting.
Then try to identify clusters of false verbal and nonverbal behavior.
But consider it only as a warning sign, not as evidence of a lie.
People who tell lies can stop moving the upper half of the body when they try to remember their fictional story, turn the toes of shoes to the door, lean towards the exit, change their posture significantly, or show "relief after the interview" - excessive relief and change of position when confession is difficult behind them.
