Climate Disaster Slowed the Economy
During the first year of the reign of Maria López Valdez, unemployment and unreliability increased in Sinaloa, foreign investment decreased and the economy with them
This is the first year of the reign of Maria López Valdez, which is called the government of change itself, which has brought great expectations in terms of economic progress, but no growth was recorded due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year, and even the main indicators of economic development were reduced.
Low February temperatures have caused millions of losses in agriculture, reduced the possibilities for growth in the state economy, resulting in a reduction in economic activity of 3.6% in the first semester of this year.
According to the report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded at 582 835 hectares of cultivated land, 78.03% of which were completely destroyed and 21.07% were found to be partial damage.
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the unemployment rate in the state increased during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 residents of Sinaloa were unemployed, representing an unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28% and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise and reached 6.19%, representing approximately 74,000 unemployed.
Less liquidity
According to Gerard López Cervantes, Director of the UAS Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on actions taken at the level of public policy.
"We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors, including loss of market liquidity due to the reduction of resources due to legislation approved by Congress in the context of the fight against money laundering. It is not easy for people who illegally seize dollars to earn, invest or use it for something," he emphasized.
Stopping Migration
López Cervantes said that a demographic factor is also involved in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who go abroad to work in the United States has decreased, both because of difficult entry and then because even if these people get abroad, it is difficult for them to get a job. People therefore remain and demand a job from our state, and thus unemployment is growing", he said.
Unreliability
According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed people in the state work without paying social security benefits.
Other features of the labour market, such as low salaries, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative territory, the lowest salaries are from all over the country, as reported by the registries of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Labour Secretariat and social planning.
The average monthly income of workers in Sinaloa was 5,352 pesetas until September, far below the national average, which is 7,375 pesetas.
Reduction of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, the most significant decline in foreign direct investment in 2011 has also been recorded in the last 10 years. According to the Ministry of Finance, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697 between January and June, representing a decrease of 87.74% compared to $5, 143,312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry for Economic Development of the Government of the State lists investments of 17 280 million pesetas per year.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government of this state asked the State Congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion pesos, which would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas to revive the economy. The local Congress approved a loan of 2 600 million pesos. By November, no debt gains were recorded in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to the representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government, Mario López Valdés, pointed to a lack of governance.
Miguel Loredo López, Chairman of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 the will of individual sectors, including the government itself, was missing.
"The development of the economy in Sinaloa was really small this year. We need to work hard to get back the land we lost this year. In 2012, we need to double our efforts, we lack harmonisation of all our efforts and, in particular, the correct and synchronised functioning of this new government. Hopefully, next year will be much better," he said.
Slowness of the economy
Loredo López said that events such as frost at the beginning of the year stopped the state economy and reduced its development and growth.
"Weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowdown of the economy, which did not recover quickly enough to restore dynamism that would enable us to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. That is why at the end of the year we found ourselves well below the expected forecasts", he said.
Re-defining the mission
According to Teodor Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, the state must be pushed towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general, we see that work is being done; we believe that a long-term plan must be prepared in which the goals and economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important that all the potential material and human resources that Sinaloa has be mobilised," he said.
The Work That Is Before Us
Chairman Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that would better manage the government's efforts.
"In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in various areas, there have been some progress in the area of economic development, but it is important to establish a long-term plan", he said.
He said that the current administration has shown progress with regard to the conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that make it possible to claim that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that there is work done here and I believe that the government is aware that there is also a lot of work ahead of us," he said.
