The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to introduce him to a new government that will face the crisis that is holding this country at risk from economic disaster and putting the entire eurozone in danger.
The presidential palace issued a report announcing that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a government composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not yet clear when the new government will take power.
Monti said he would present the President with the results of his talks with political parties in an effort to form a government.
"I want to confirm that I have absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult stage," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti explicitly did not say that he would be able to create a government, but the tone of his comments suggested that obstacles were overcome.
"The frame is now well marked," he added.
Monti completed the process of creating a government in less than three days, much shorter than usual. Meanwhile, Italy is trying to combat the political and financial crisis, which has led to an unsustainable level of debt.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough package of austerity measures required by European leaders, which will be the only way to restore Italy's damaged credibility.
There's a lot of pressure on Monti to hurry up, and because of the instability of the markets, interest on Italian BTP bonds with a 10-year maturity of 7 percentage points exceeded the level at which Greece and Ireland had to apply for rescue.
