Any obstacle or delay in the effort could trigger a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has joined the pressure and warns that Monti’s failure could be catastrophic.
Monti started negotiations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, youth and women’s organisations on Monday.
The round will end on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed president of Napolitan on Sunday, which allowed very rapid action in response to the crisis.
After a brief drop from the end of last week, when it was already clear that Berlusconi would resign, the interest on Italian bonds returned to a critical threshold, thus responding to the uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would succeed.
Saving Italy, whose public debt is 1.8 trillion euro, would be beyond the scope of the current euro area financial reserves.
