We're lucky to be able to look at the places we've always wanted.
We couldn't have done better.
What did it mean to you that you were an important part of the origin of the grunge genre?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group, in which all the greats are represented.
The Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains are our friends.
Surprisingly, when a movement emerges from a group of friends, it does not happen very often.
From time to time, a group is formed in the city, but it is much less common for five to ten groups to emerge from one city at a time.
We're proud of it, and we're honored to be part of the Seattle group.
Sometimes we still play with some.
Last year we were at the Alice in Chains festival and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour. We are lucky that they are all our friends and we are honored that we can be part of this movement that originated in Seattle.
It's also very unusual for a group like yours to stick together and still have the same members after all these years.
Yes, the four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which in itself is much longer than the usual duration of the group.
I think, first of all, we're all lucky that we're still in this world, and second of all, the fact that we're constantly interested in each other plays a role.
We are all close friends, and thanks to that we have managed to open up musical paths that allow everyone sufficient freedom to experiment.
We trust each other, we appreciate each other's music, and I don't think it could be better.
Your relationship to the word fame was not easy, but thanks to your success you can do what you like.
How do you find your balance?
As we grew, it became easier and easier to find balance.
We try not to go on tour too much because it is very easy to fall into this trap of crowds and people who love our music.
When you realize that people came for music, you remind yourself that you have to respect music and what you gave her, and you can't let yourself get carried away by being famous, rock stars, and neither of us ever really cared about that.
How do you remember the next Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote great songs, and at first, it was something spectacular.
As a band, we existed for three years and never released an album until after Andy Woods died.
It was very frustrating because it took so long. The most important thing is that today we are friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us. When I listen to a song or look at pictures, I remember Andy, how incredible he was, how I laughed with him. It was always a pleasure to work with him, laugh, talk about music or football and many others.
She was an incredible person, and we miss her so much.
The national band Las Robertas will be assigned to launch a show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose them as openings?
Yes, production has sent us videos with several suggestions and we liked this group the most. Therefore, we are wondering what Las Robertas will offer live and must be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the words of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's an Ed question, so I don't know.
He's singing it, and I think he's adding the first thing to his mind.
Who influences you as a bass player?
A lot of people.
The first thing I can think of is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C.J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There's so many of them that I could talk all night about bass players I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to hold the grunge even though it's no longer in style?
I think we've all always felt slightly separated from the word grunge.
When it comes to grunge, I think of the groups I mentioned as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came into existence at the same time, and if music is so valid today, it's something great, because it's music that's worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are playing better music today than ever.
At the beginning, your music had a slightly bleak character and is now more positive.
What is behind this change?
That's interesting, because I feel that there are a few songs in the new album that are easier to play, but there are also songs like The End or Juste Breathe, which are considered very bleak, although they may sound positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried, and they're deeply dark songs.
I think that when you grow up and have some trauma in your life, you lose someone from your family or your boyfriend, these things start to affect your art and music, and these two songs represent this to me.
I also think you can be a happy person and still make gloomy music.
