Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jacome presented details of the plane crash that killed the Governor's secretary, Francisco Blake, and seven others.
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident investigation in which the Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and seven others died show that the helicopter landed directly on the terrain with full force without the pilot having a chance to attempt forced landing.
At a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jacome, Secretary for Communication and Transport, said that before the start of the aircraft the pilot stated that climate conditions allow flight.
"Parts that appear suggest that the unit has come into contact with the terrain several times, the wings are entangled in the tree branches 25 meters from where the unit lost the hull".
He also informed that the unit was intended for 19 people, so it met all requirements for the transport of personnel.
In addition, he stated that no components were found on the ground on the basis of an investigation carried out in the field of impact.
"When searching, it was found that the parts of the aircraft were not located elsewhere, so the aircraft hit the mainland as integral.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 people, meeting all requirements for the transport of persons.
The terrain shows a slope with a slope of seven to thirty degrees.
The secretary assured that at the moment the most important thing is to get results as quickly as possible. However, the investigation may take several months or up to one year.
Gilberto López Meyer, managing director of airports and auxiliary services, said that at the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff was moving at a cruise speed and the accident occurred on a soft ascending terrain.
"This information supports the hypothesis that it was a routine overflight operation at the time of the accident," he said.
At a press conference, SCT representative Pérez Jacome listed six basic points of investigation:
Visual flight:
In accordance with the aviation standards, the flight was carried out according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must see the terrain during the flight.
Meteorological conditions:
The AICM reports indicate adequate conditions at take-off, according to which the aircraft moves towards the border, between DF and the State of Mexico there were visible layers of clouds at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the clouds the crew was looking for a lower area and greater visibility up to the valley of Cuernavaca.
Impact location.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the helicopter from the radar match, it is likely that there was no loss of control or disruption of the trajectory of the flight prior to the impact.
Dissipation of aircraft residues in restricted territory:
The information we currently have allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight trajectory and from the side.
A diagram of the dispersal of the aircraft remains indicates that the helicopter was complete at the time of the impact on the mainland.
There was no fire or explosion.
There was no evidence of an explosion or fire at the scene of the accident.
The latest results of the investigation show that there may have been several contacts with the mainland.
During off-road work, aircraft remains were found at a height of up to 9200 feet above sea level, the terrain is sloped, the slope goes from seven to 30 degrees.
The photographs show footage of the likely breakdown along the route.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter could have come into contact with the ground in several places.
After a careful search around the accident, in a territory that is more extensive than the designated area, no remains of the helicopter were found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a state when the helicopter was still solid.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance has begun researching the gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research to discover the gene responsible for obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it conducts research to detect a gene causing obesity in children and young people. A research called "Genetics of Obesity in Children and Teens" will enable the results of overweight.
In a report by the head of the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and pupils from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
People can come to the IMSS sports centres in Valle de México, where every Saturday from 8 o'clock will be tested for minors.
He stressed that research began at the Cuauhtémoc Sports Centre (Mexican State) and since 8 October this activity is also carried out at the Zahualcóyolt Sports Centre (East of the Mexican State).
Once data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Centre (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to trace risk factors to Mexican children and young people and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on November 14, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined every Saturday, and genes are examined (trying to identify genes involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said that this research reflects the concern of health professionals over the alarming increase in child weight.
'The health polls carried out between 1999 and 2006 showed that only six years later boys had a 77% increase in obesity and 47% increase in girls. A dramatic increase was also seen in the case of overweight', said an expert from IMSS.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators was the assumption that the population of the country differed from other populations by its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetics, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that general obesity genetics are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and which is stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of the participants is that they receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus establishing whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the probability that the individual will suffer from metabolic problems and pre-sugar conditions.
So far, the information is confidential, it is handed over by doctors to parents in writing and explained to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes that they need to make in order to avoid disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life, meaning a lack of daily physical activity, a day’s sitting in front of television and the use of means of transport instead of walking for short distances.
Overweight also causes large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no potholes in Asphalt from UNAM
Rafael Herrera, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty of UNAM creates modified asphalt with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, regardless of climatic conditions and temperature
If the paving was properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Region, Rafael Herrera Najer, a scientist from the Chemical Faculty (FQ) of UNAM, who also added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt tiles were adequate, there would be a significant reduction of potholes, or even could be completely removed.
In his lecture, the technological cause of the potholes he made during the International Year of Chemistry announced that the laboratory under his leadership was developing modified asphalt with polymers, which should create a mixture of similar characteristics to asphalt, but also greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, thus improving functionality and reducing pothole formation.
He explained that asphalt, the hardest part of oil, is the formation of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with large molecular weights called asphalt, and others with low molecular weights called mortars. Together, they give asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscoelastic nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it acts as a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost solid, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to weather conditions and temperature, warned the expert on chemical engineering.
A scientist at the Chemical Faculty observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers is an asphalt insert, made up of small stones embedded in asphalt and then compressed.
He emphasized that every stone that makes up the insert is covered with asphalt.
When passing cars or creating pressure it is so possible that the forces in the pavement are well decomposed.
If it were modified asphalt, they would have decomposed even better, thinks a chemical engineer.
He added that the last layer called the cape, made up of fine stones, also covered in asphalt, is placed on the asphalt insert.
As this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rims, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt liner and ensure friction of the road.
As a part of the paving, it will be exposed to heavy loads, it must have sufficient thickness and be careful of the material from which it is made.
Climate, especially moisture and temperature changes, are also a very important factor to bear in mind. In particular, water has a great influence on the functionality of the asphalt liner.
Once the terrain is wet, the water spreads in and it's hard to get out, it causes softening of all layers of the pavement and thus creating potholes.
He explained that during the construction of potholes, the first film of the casing will be damaged and only then the asphalt liner will be damaged. However, the damage does not occur in one moment, but it is a slow process that should be stopped at the first stamps using suitable maintenance programs.
