On November 4th of last year, a fingerprint expert from CTI in Cali entered history as a man who confirmed the identity of the Supreme Leader Farc: "Alphonse Cana" by comparing fingerprints.
Of the seven fingerprint experts working at CTI this week, Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejad, has been working in the field of judicial research for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career González worked at the town hall in Chocó, where he often had to go through the forest for more than five days to get to the place where the corpses had to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital city of Valle and after taking the relevant courses, he began specializing in fingerprints. This science deals with the study of skin friction, i.e. palms and legs.
In the week of the operation against the said Alfons Cane, Eliaszar was told to take his clothes with him for at least three days.
Something big was expected.
On Friday night he went to Cauca in a helicopter from Palmiro.
He knew that he would have to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected of being the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so they asked him to take a fingerprint card from Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigating team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it because of physical appearances.
He didn't have a beard, he was dressed like a villager in the area, without glasses, much thinner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Along with the galton magnifying glass, ink and transplanter and light, Eliaszar began to compare the dactyl records of the corpse to the card entries.
The eye did not disappoint him: it was Alfonso Cano.
That same night, a man from Puerto Tejada was commissioned to confirm to the Secretary of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, whether he really was the supreme commander of Farc.
Track Search
For the Sijin de Cali dactyloscope, the recognition given to Eliazar González by President Juan Manuel Santos at the press conference of the operational service against "Cano" is very important.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, without the possibility of error, which can play a key role in the decision-making of crimes.
In addition to identifying the corpses, these people help research crimes like theft or murder and confirm the identity of the captured.
When they get caught, a lot of delinquents present fake IDs or don't have papers at all.
We'll take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that in the event of an injury, he had to remove a piece of the house wall, because in this place the thief leaned on to pull out a safe full of jewelry and money.
The walls are difficult because they are not intended for fingerprinting, but in this case we were able to get a whole hand print and identify the perpetrator who was involved in several thefts", he recalled.
Fingerprints can also confirm or disprove suspicion in a murder case.
Recently, they found a dead man with bottles of alcohol around him.
The investigation revealed that one of the family members might be responsible for the murder, and the print on the bottle actually confirmed it.
Although there's no way to confirm that he really was a killer, it's obvious that he appeared on the scene of a crime.
The fingerprint expert from CTI explained that the objects are "marked with chemical or physical reactive substances".
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to collect them.
