Nord Stream, a new port of entry for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream long-distance pipeline connecting Eastern Europe directly to Russia and led down the Baltic Sea has begun to operate.
It must deliver gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, among them four heads of state and government, participated in Nord Stream’s inauguration, a new pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
The symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte have jointly turned the control around the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic metres of Russian gas will flow to Western Europe every year through the first 1 224 km pipeline connecting the Saint Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklemburg-Pomorany.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow the supply of a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, which is a quantity equal to the whole of French consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route is already mentioned.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building has the character of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries strongly protested against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany without being led on the ground by a third State (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing a little bit of power: the possibility of pushing Russia through threats to close its access to Western European markets is becoming more difficult for them.
Warsaw expressed this most strongly when she did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
It means that it is a politically sensitive topic.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe has gained greater confidence in its purchases.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created cracks between Europeans from the east and the west.
Russia was able to assert its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries with high gas consumption, whose deposits are nearing their end.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us", confirmed François Fillon during the opening ceremony of this pipeline and demonstrated the point at which large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All of this explains the broad smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The underwater pipe is made of steel fitted with a concrete casing in order to protect it from anchors of seagoing vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"For security reasons, almost a hundred of them had to be removed or destroyed," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing as 242 Eiffel Tower, which is not interrupted by valves or maintenance stations at all.
One control platform was to be built near Sweden, but the project leaders rejected it when the Swedes were not eager to see the Russian state company permanently settling off their coasts.
"In case of a malfunction, we stop the gas flow in less than 1 minute", explains Jens Müller.
In case of leaks, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by builders, for welds were designed to create leaks once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline outside is checked by an underwater robot towed by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device circulating inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 metre is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is pushed by gas.
In the finish line, 3 m/s will provide accurate information on any deformations of metal parts over the entire three days of the journey.
The remote pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply secured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
Five companies joined forces to implement this project.
Gazprom's leadership remains, which holds a 51% stake.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each) as well as Dutch company Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company has its registered office in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased all its gas transport capacities to the company for five years by a contract that can be renewed.
"Gazprom will have a profit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of the actual gas being transported", explains Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided by 30% shareholder and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of work should reach EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For the GDF Suez Group, investment costs thus increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will come back to them, because Gazprom alone takes the risk.
The pipeline exits from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The valves of a height of 4.5 meters form an output gas gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before it is transported to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
When full capacity is reached, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
Moleskine - designer notebook
The Italian company Moleskine, which was founded 50 years ago, wants to rekindle the joy of writing.
It brings the smell of adventure, the hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable with its black rectangular plates and its white leaves as if aged over time.
After all, Moleskin's notebook, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
At that time, the Italian company Modo Modo based in Milan decides to launch a new design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant working for the company, takes up the launch of a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique "moleskin" (imitation of the skin), which is used for example for surface adjustment of benches.
This type of notebook was greatly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has returned to popularity an old and forgotten object that was an icon of avant-garde artists until the XXth century", relates Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the leader of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to settle on 12.7 million units last year.
The situation is remote from the secret production from the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were made.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and is exported to 70 countries from France to the United States.
It is difficult to build an artificial portrait of the buyer, because the notebook will impress the businessman as well as the student or professional.
The image of Moleskine's notebook includes that its owners are people of cosmopolitan, cultured, and open spirit.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its early years, has now had almost a hundred and since 2008 has two offices, one of which is in Milan and the other in New York.
He sends his notebooks to the bookstore and through a chain of FNAC stores to small boutiques in the middle of cities where he could assert his identity.
"We have observed the spirit of the time and this need for new writing, through the turbulent development of e-mails", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of the Moleskine notebook: recently the brand opened the exhibition " Zacházka", where architects or artists display their notebook.
In August, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival, she also introduced new records of a notebook resembling a leopard.
Moleskine benefits from its success and this cultural aura and diversifies its products: bags, diaries, pencils, laptop cases ... The brand is extended to a variety of carriers.
Success that aroused envy: in autumn 2006 Modo Modo was bought by investment funds SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of handicapped workers so high?
About 19% of handicapped people are looking for work.
Today opens 15. Week for employing handicapped people.
Despite the electoral public policy introduced in 2005, the percentage of unemployed handicapped persons is twice as high as the average, i.e. 19% compared to 9% for the entire population.
Is it daunting?
"No, underscores Éric Blanchet, CEO of the Adaptt Association, who organizes the Week for employing handicapped people."
"The progress achieved in 15 years is remarkable."
"At that time, the percentage of unemployed was not twice, but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that there are numerous obstacles for unemployed handicapped persons before their entry into work.
These are elderly: 37% have more than 50 years (17% on average).
They have low qualifications: 80% have no graduation and out of 2.3 million university students, only 10,000 are handicapped.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for handicapped people compared to 38% on average.
In short, these are the criteria which make it particularly difficult to return to employment and which represent the "core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, founded in 1992, to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
So much for objective brakes.
There are unsaid ways of thinking that are certainly evolving, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité found that the questioned managers have a "weak level of knowledge about handicapped people" with an "exaggeration about people in wheelchairs and mental or mental deficiencies".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the objective of employing 6% of handicapped workers as laid down in the 1987 Law.
The last known numbers dating back to 2008, indicate a state equal to 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, charged with charging companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence is the number of" fined" enterprises, as well as the amounts paid, which fell from 59,000 more guilty enterprises to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euro) between 2007 and 2011.
"The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc."
"But this improvement also demonstrates true awareness, especially in large enterprises."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of businesses with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers compared to 82% of businesses with 100 to 199 employees.
